  1. The price variable appears to have some extreme values. Remove the outliers in the âpriceâ variable using the IQR method. IQR and quantile functions throw error if you have NAs in your variable. Use na.rm=TRUE option inside IQR and quantile methods to ignore the missing price values
q1 <- quantile(realtor$price, na.rm = TRUE)[2]  # First quartile
q3 <- quantile(realtor$price, na.rm = TRUE)[4]  # Third quartile
iqr <- IQR(realtor$price, na.rm = TRUE)  # Interquartile Range

# Calculate lower and upper bounds to define outliers
lower_bound <- q1 - 1.5 * iqr
upper_bound <- q3 + 1.5 * iqr

# Subset the data frame to remove outliers in the "price" variable
cleaned_data <- realtor[realtor$price >= lower_bound & realtor$price <= upper_bound, ]
summary(cleaned_data)

  1. Is there a statistically significant difference between the average house price for different states? Use appropriate plot and statistic test to answer this question
boxplot(realtor$price ~ realtor$state, data = realtor, main = "Boxplot of House Prices by State", xlab = "State", ylab = "Price")


library(ggplot2)
library(stats)


anova_result <- aov(realtor$price ~ realtor$state, data = realtor)
print(summary(anova_result))

  1. Convert all categorical variables to âfactorâ using factor function ( set the âlabelsâ option to give meaningful names/labels to each level)
HeartDisease$sex <- factor(HeartDisease$sex, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("Female", "Male"))

# Convert cp variable to factor with custom labels
HeartDisease$cp <- factor(HeartDisease$cp, levels = c(1, 2, 3, 4), labels = c("Typical Angina", "Atypical Angina", "Non-anginal Pain", "Asymptomatic"))

# Convert fbs variable to factor with custom labels
HeartDisease$fbs <- factor(HeartDisease$fbs, levels = c(0, 1), labels = c("<= 120 mg/dl", "> 120 mg/dl"))

Mode <- function(x) {
  ux <- unique(x)
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}

# Calculate median
median_age <- median(HeartDisease$age, na.rm = TRUE)

# Calculate mode
mode_age <- Mode(HeartDisease$age)

# Print the results
print(paste("Median age:", median_age))
[1] "Median age: 54"
print(paste("Mode age:", mode_age))
[1] "Mode age: 54"

# Function to perform t-test and plot side-by-side boxplot for numeric variables with two groups
test_and_plot_numeric_t_test <- function(data, numeric_variable, categorical_variable) {
  t_test <- t.test(data[[numeric_variable]] ~ data[[categorical_variable]])
  print(paste("T-test p-value for", numeric_variable, "and", categorical_variable, ":", format(t_test$p.value, scientific = FALSE)))
  ggplot(data, aes(x = diagnosis, y = .data[[numeric_variable]], fill = .data[[categorical_variable]])) +
    geom_boxplot(position = position_dodge()) +
    labs(title = paste("Side-by-Side Box Plot of", numeric_variable, "by", categorical_variable, "and Diagnosis"),
         x = "Diagnosis", y = numeric_variable) +
    theme_minimal()
}

# Apply function to each numeric continuous variable
test_and_plot_numeric_t_test(HeartDisease, "age", "diagnosis")
[1] "T-test p-value for age and diagnosis : 0.000000000000000004842782"

test_and_plot_numeric_t_test(HeartDisease, "trestbps", "diagnosis")
[1] "T-test p-value for trestbps and diagnosis : 0.001485277"

test_and_plot_numeric_t_test(HeartDisease, "chol", "diagnosis")
[1] "T-test p-value for chol and diagnosis : 0.0000000000001951116"

test_and_plot_numeric_t_test(HeartDisease, "thalach", "diagnosis")
[1] "T-test p-value for thalach and diagnosis : 0.000000000000000000000000000000001301582"

[1] "T-test p-value for oldpeak and diagnosis : 0.0000000000000000000000000000000005077156"

# Function to perform chi-squared test and plot mosaic plot for categorical variables
test_and_plot_categorical <- function(data, variable) {
  contingency_table <- table(data$diagnosis, data[[variable]])
  chi_squared_test <- chisq.test(contingency_table)
  print(paste("Chi-squared test p-value for", variable, ":", format(chi_squared_test$p.value, scientific = FALSE)))
  mosaicplot(contingency_table, main = paste("Mosaic Plot of", variable, "by Diagnosis"), color = TRUE)
}

# Apply function to each categorical nominal variable
test_and_plot_categorical(HeartDisease, "sex") 
[1] "Chi-squared test p-value for sex : 0.00000000000000000002485453"

test_and_plot_categorical(HeartDisease, "fbs")
[1] "Chi-squared test p-value for fbs : 0.00005971604"

test_and_plot_categorical(HeartDisease, "restecg")
[1] "Chi-squared test p-value for restecg : 0.002862841"

test_and_plot_categorical(HeartDisease, "exang")
[1] "Chi-squared test p-value for exang : 0.000000000000000000000000000000000000000006422657"
